Date: Sat, 19 Jul 2025 15:39:41 +0530
Subject: [PATCH 2/7] UPSTREAM:PROTOCOL:CP:HOSTAPD: Add Robust AV Streaming and
 SCS capability support

Introduce support for Robust AV Streaming and Stream
Classification Service (SCS) as per IEEE 802.11 QoS enhancements.

- Add `scs` config flag in BSS config to enable SCS support
- Advertise SCS capability in vendor-specific IE (WFA capability)
  in Beacon, Probe Resp, and Assoc Resp frames
- Enable SCS support in Extended Capabilities (bits 51, 54)

This patch introduces a new hostapd configuration option to
control Stream Classification Service (SCS) support. When
`enable_scs` is set, hostapd will handle SCS requests and
advertise capability accordingly.

Spec Reference: IEEE Std 802.11-2024 - Section 11.25

Refer to IEEE Std 802.11-2024 Section 11.25.2 SCS Procedures
(Stream Classification Service) for more details.

SCS Overview:
-------------------------------------------------------------------
A non-AP STA may request SCS by sending an SCS Request frame
containing one or more descriptors marked as “Add” or “Change.”
These descriptors define how MSDUs are to be classified and
prioritized.

Downlink (DL) SCS:
    - The STA may specify a User Priority (UP) or TID, optionally
along with QoS characteristics such as Service Interval, Delay Bound,
and Throughput.
    - TCLAS elements (e.g., Type 4: Source/Destination IP, Protocol,
Ports) are used to identify the traffic flow. The AP uses these
parameters to classify and prioritize matching MSDUs in the downlink
direction.

Uplink (UL) SCS:
    - The STA provides only QoS characteristics (no TCLAS or
intra-access category).
    - The AP uses these parameters to schedule trigger frames to
fetch uplink data from the STA.

Upon receiving an SCS Request, the AP may accept or decline it.
If accepted:
For DL: The AP classifies and prioritizes matching downlink traffic
using the specified TID.
For UL: The AP initiates trigger-based uplink scheduling based on the
QoS parameters.

